5-mm section thickness) reveal diffuse enlargement of the pancreas, which has a featureless appearance with loss of lobular architecture and narrowing of the MPD (arrow in <b>b</b>). Pseudocyst formation, a rare manifestation, is also seen (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d–f)</b> Axial precontrast <b>(d)</b> and postcontrast arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and venous phase <b>(f)</b> fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR images (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) reveal hyperintensity within the pancreatic tail and heterogeneous postcontrast enhancement. The low-signal-intensity peripheral rind (arrow) is a characteristic finding. <b>(g, h)</b> ERCP images reveal smooth narrowing of the distal CBD (arrow in <b>g</b>) with diffuse “irregular” narrowing of the MPD (arrowheads in <b>h</b>). Laboratory evaluation revealed a significantly elevated IgG4 level of over 5 g/L (normal range, 0.06–1.21 g/L), a finding consistent with autoimmune pancreatitis. Steroid therapy was initiated. <b>(i)</b> ERCP image obtained 6 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows resolution of the biliary stricture and normalization of the contour and caliber of the MPD (arrows). <b>(j)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 12 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows a reduction in the size of the pancreas and resolution of inflammatory changes (arrow). The renal lesions are also less conspicuous (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F1G">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1H" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g01h.jpeg" height="1800" width="1064" aria-labelledby="F1H" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1h.</b>  Autoimmune pancreatitis in a 38-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan through the upper abdomen reveals diffuse enlargement of the pancreas with a peripheral rind of hypoattenuation (black arrow), involution of the pancreatic tail, and narrowing of the splenic vein (white arrow). Note also the associated multiple bilateral hypoattenuating renal lesions (arrowheads), which represent foci of tubulointerstitial nephritis. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial non-fat-suppressed <b>(b)</b> and fat-suppressed <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images (repetition time msec/echo time msec = 1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) reveal diffuse enlargement of the pancreas, which has a featureless appearance with loss of lobular architecture and narrowing of the MPD (arrow in <b>b</b>). Pseudocyst formation, a rare manifestation, is also seen (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d–f)</b> Axial precontrast <b>(d)</b> and postcontrast arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and venous phase <b>(f)</b> fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR images (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) reveal hyperintensity within the pancreatic tail and heterogeneous postcontrast enhancement. The low-signal-intensity peripheral rind (arrow) is a characteristic finding. <b>(g, h)</b> ERCP images reveal smooth narrowing of the distal CBD (arrow in <b>g</b>) with diffuse “irregular” narrowing of the MPD (arrowheads in <b>h</b>). Laboratory evaluation revealed a significantly elevated IgG4 level of over 5 g/L (normal range, 0.06–1.21 g/L), a finding consistent with autoimmune pancreatitis. Steroid therapy was initiated. <b>(i)</b> ERCP image obtained 6 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows resolution of the biliary stricture and normalization of the contour and caliber of the MPD (arrows). <b>(j)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 12 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows a reduction in the size of the pancreas and resolution of inflammatory changes (arrow). The renal lesions are also less conspicuous (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F1H">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1I" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g01i.jpeg" height="1800" width="984" aria-labelledby="F1I" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1i.</b>  Autoimmune pancreatitis in a 38-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan through the upper abdomen reveals diffuse enlargement of the pancreas with a peripheral rind of hypoattenuation (black arrow), involution of the pancreatic tail, and narrowing of the splenic vein (white arrow). Note also the associated multiple bilateral hypoattenuating renal lesions (arrowheads), which represent foci of tubulointerstitial nephritis. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial non-fat-suppressed <b>(b)</b> and fat-suppressed <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images (repetition time msec/echo time msec = 1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) reveal diffuse enlargement of the pancreas, which has a featureless appearance with loss of lobular architecture and narrowing of the MPD (arrow in <b>b</b>). Pseudocyst formation, a rare manifestation, is also seen (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d–f)</b> Axial precontrast <b>(d)</b> and postcontrast arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and venous phase <b>(f)</b> fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR images (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) reveal hyperintensity within the pancreatic tail and heterogeneous postcontrast enhancement. The low-signal-intensity peripheral rind (arrow) is a characteristic finding. <b>(g, h)</b> ERCP images reveal smooth narrowing of the distal CBD (arrow in <b>g</b>) with diffuse “irregular” narrowing of the MPD (arrowheads in <b>h</b>). Laboratory evaluation revealed a significantly elevated IgG4 level of over 5 g/L (normal range, 0.06–1.21 g/L), a finding consistent with autoimmune pancreatitis. Steroid therapy was initiated. <b>(i)</b> ERCP image obtained 6 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows resolution of the biliary stricture and normalization of the contour and caliber of the MPD (arrows). <b>(j)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 12 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows a reduction in the size of the pancreas and resolution of inflammatory changes (arrow). The renal lesions are also less conspicuous (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F1I">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1J" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g01j.jpeg" height="1628" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1J" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1j.</b>  Autoimmune pancreatitis in a 38-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan through the upper abdomen reveals diffuse enlargement of the pancreas with a peripheral rind of hypoattenuation (black arrow), involution of the pancreatic tail, and narrowing of the splenic vein (white arrow). Note also the associated multiple bilateral hypoattenuating renal lesions (arrowheads), which represent foci of tubulointerstitial nephritis. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial non-fat-suppressed <b>(b)</b> and fat-suppressed <b>(c)</b> T2-weighted MR images (repetition time msec/echo time msec = 1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) reveal diffuse enlargement of the pancreas, which has a featureless appearance with loss of lobular architecture and narrowing of the MPD (arrow in <b>b</b>). Pseudocyst formation, a rare manifestation, is also seen (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d–f)</b> Axial precontrast <b>(d)</b> and postcontrast arterial phase <b>(e)</b> and venous phase <b>(f)</b> fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR images (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) reveal hyperintensity within the pancreatic tail and heterogeneous postcontrast enhancement. The low-signal-intensity peripheral rind (arrow) is a characteristic finding. <b>(g, h)</b> ERCP images reveal smooth narrowing of the distal CBD (arrow in <b>g</b>) with diffuse “irregular” narrowing of the MPD (arrowheads in <b>h</b>). Laboratory evaluation revealed a significantly elevated IgG4 level of over 5 g/L (normal range, 0.06–1.21 g/L), a finding consistent with autoimmune pancreatitis. Steroid therapy was initiated. <b>(i)</b> ERCP image obtained 6 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows resolution of the biliary stricture and normalization of the contour and caliber of the MPD (arrows). <b>(j)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 12 months after the completion of steroid therapy shows a reduction in the size of the pancreas and resolution of inflammatory changes (arrow). The renal lesions are also less conspicuous (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F1J">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13c02x.jpeg" height="1067" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2.</b>  Groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall. Drawing illustrates the disease process in groove pancreatitis. Inflammation is predominantly centered in the pancreaticoduodenal groove, with multiple cystic lesions within the medial wall of the duodenum <i>(D)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g03a.jpeg" height="1538" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image through the pancreas <i>(P)</i> demonstrates a sheetlike hypoechoic area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove with areas of cystic change (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase CT scans show a hypoattenuating area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow in <b>b</b>) with inflammatory stranding within the surrounding fat and in the right anterior pararenalparaduodenal space (arrows in <b>c</b>). <i>P</i> = pancreas. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR images (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) show hyperintense cystic lesions (arrowhead) within the thickened duodenal wall with minimally hyperintense soft tissue in the groove (arrow). <i>D</i> = second part of duodenum, <i>P</i> = pancreatic head. <b>(f)</b> Coronal delayed contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image (3.4/1.5, 3.75-mm section thickness) obtained 5 minutes after the injection of gadolinium-based contrast material shows partially enhanced cystic lesions (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. Histopathologic analysis of multiple surgical biopsy specimens showed pancreatic heterotopia, Brunner gland hyperplasia, and pancreatitis, findings that are consistent with the diagnosis of groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g03b.jpeg" height="1265" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image through the pancreas <i>(P)</i> demonstrates a sheetlike hypoechoic area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove with areas of cystic change (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase CT scans show a hypoattenuating area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow in <b>b</b>) with inflammatory stranding within the surrounding fat and in the right anterior pararenalparaduodenal space (arrows in <b>c</b>). <i>P</i> = pancreas. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR images (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) show hyperintense cystic lesions (arrowhead) within the thickened duodenal wall with minimally hyperintense soft tissue in the groove (arrow). <i>D</i> = second part of duodenum, <i>P</i> = pancreatic head. <b>(f)</b> Coronal delayed contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image (3.4/1.5, 3.75-mm section thickness) obtained 5 minutes after the injection of gadolinium-based contrast material shows partially enhanced cystic lesions (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. Histopathologic analysis of multiple surgical biopsy specimens showed pancreatic heterotopia, Brunner gland hyperplasia, and pancreatitis, findings that are consistent with the diagnosis of groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g03c.jpeg" height="1315" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image through the pancreas <i>(P)</i> demonstrates a sheetlike hypoechoic area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove with areas of cystic change (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase CT scans show a hypoattenuating area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow in <b>b</b>) with inflammatory stranding within the surrounding fat and in the right anterior pararenalparaduodenal space (arrows in <b>c</b>). <i>P</i> = pancreas. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR images (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) show hyperintense cystic lesions (arrowhead) within the thickened duodenal wall with minimally hyperintense soft tissue in the groove (arrow). <i>D</i> = second part of duodenum, <i>P</i> = pancreatic head. <b>(f)</b> Coronal delayed contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image (3.4/1.5, 3.75-mm section thickness) obtained 5 minutes after the injection of gadolinium-based contrast material shows partially enhanced cystic lesions (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. Histopathologic analysis of multiple surgical biopsy specimens showed pancreatic heterotopia, Brunner gland hyperplasia, and pancreatitis, findings that are consistent with the diagnosis of groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g03d.jpeg" height="1326" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3d.</b>  Groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image through the pancreas <i>(P)</i> demonstrates a sheetlike hypoechoic area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove with areas of cystic change (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase CT scans show a hypoattenuating area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow in <b>b</b>) with inflammatory stranding within the surrounding fat and in the right anterior pararenalparaduodenal space (arrows in <b>c</b>). <i>P</i> = pancreas. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR images (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) show hyperintense cystic lesions (arrowhead) within the thickened duodenal wall with minimally hyperintense soft tissue in the groove (arrow). <i>D</i> = second part of duodenum, <i>P</i> = pancreatic head. <b>(f)</b> Coronal delayed contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image (3.4/1.5, 3.75-mm section thickness) obtained 5 minutes after the injection of gadolinium-based contrast material shows partially enhanced cystic lesions (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. Histopathologic analysis of multiple surgical biopsy specimens showed pancreatic heterotopia, Brunner gland hyperplasia, and pancreatitis, findings that are consistent with the diagnosis of groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F3D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g03e.jpeg" height="1601" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3e.</b>  Groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image through the pancreas <i>(P)</i> demonstrates a sheetlike hypoechoic area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove with areas of cystic change (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase CT scans show a hypoattenuating area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow in <b>b</b>) with inflammatory stranding within the surrounding fat and in the right anterior pararenalparaduodenal space (arrows in <b>c</b>). <i>P</i> = pancreas. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR images (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) show hyperintense cystic lesions (arrowhead) within the thickened duodenal wall with minimally hyperintense soft tissue in the groove (arrow). <i>D</i> = second part of duodenum, <i>P</i> = pancreatic head. <b>(f)</b> Coronal delayed contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image (3.4/1.5, 3.75-mm section thickness) obtained 5 minutes after the injection of gadolinium-based contrast material shows partially enhanced cystic lesions (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. Histopathologic analysis of multiple surgical biopsy specimens showed pancreatic heterotopia, Brunner gland hyperplasia, and pancreatitis, findings that are consistent with the diagnosis of groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F3E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g03f.jpeg" height="1592" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3f.</b>  Groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall. <b>(a)</b> Transverse US image through the pancreas <i>(P)</i> demonstrates a sheetlike hypoechoic area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove with areas of cystic change (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Venous phase CT scans show a hypoattenuating area in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrow in <b>b</b>) with inflammatory stranding within the surrounding fat and in the right anterior pararenalparaduodenal space (arrows in <b>c</b>). <i>P</i> = pancreas. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial <b>(d)</b> and coronal <b>(e)</b> non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR images (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) show hyperintense cystic lesions (arrowhead) within the thickened duodenal wall with minimally hyperintense soft tissue in the groove (arrow). <i>D</i> = second part of duodenum, <i>P</i> = pancreatic head. <b>(f)</b> Coronal delayed contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image (3.4/1.5, 3.75-mm section thickness) obtained 5 minutes after the injection of gadolinium-based contrast material shows partially enhanced cystic lesions (arrow) in the pancreaticoduodenal groove. Histopathologic analysis of multiple surgical biopsy specimens showed pancreatic heterotopia, Brunner gland hyperplasia, and pancreatitis, findings that are consistent with the diagnosis of groove pancreatitis with cystic dystrophy of the duodenal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F3F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g04a.jpeg" height="1202" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Tropical pancreatitis in a 23-year-old man of southern Indian descent who presented with recurrent attacks of pancreatitis with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a markedly dilated and tortuous MPD (arrow) with large intraductal stones (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple large areas of calcification and intraductal “stones” in the pancreatic head (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Coronal non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1000/77, 3-mm section thickness) shows a markedly dilated MPD <i>(D)</i>, with intraductal stones appearing as hypointense filling defects (arrowheads). Note the significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(d, e)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) <b>(d)</b> and ERCP images obtained after the injection of contrast material into the CBD (left) and MPD (right) <b>(e)</b> show gross pancreatic ductal dilatation with intraductal calculi (arrows). No pancreatic masses or ductal anomalies were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g04b.jpeg" height="1240" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Tropical pancreatitis in a 23-year-old man of southern Indian descent who presented with recurrent attacks of pancreatitis with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a markedly dilated and tortuous MPD (arrow) with large intraductal stones (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple large areas of calcification and intraductal “stones” in the pancreatic head (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Coronal non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1000/77, 3-mm section thickness) shows a markedly dilated MPD <i>(D)</i>, with intraductal stones appearing as hypointense filling defects (arrowheads). Note the significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(d, e)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) <b>(d)</b> and ERCP images obtained after the injection of contrast material into the CBD (left) and MPD (right) <b>(e)</b> show gross pancreatic ductal dilatation with intraductal calculi (arrows). No pancreatic masses or ductal anomalies were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g04c.jpeg" height="1246" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Tropical pancreatitis in a 23-year-old man of southern Indian descent who presented with recurrent attacks of pancreatitis with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a markedly dilated and tortuous MPD (arrow) with large intraductal stones (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple large areas of calcification and intraductal “stones” in the pancreatic head (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Coronal non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1000/77, 3-mm section thickness) shows a markedly dilated MPD <i>(D)</i>, with intraductal stones appearing as hypointense filling defects (arrowheads). Note the significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(d, e)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) <b>(d)</b> and ERCP images obtained after the injection of contrast material into the CBD (left) and MPD (right) <b>(e)</b> show gross pancreatic ductal dilatation with intraductal calculi (arrows). No pancreatic masses or ductal anomalies were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g04d.jpeg" height="1233" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4d.</b>  Tropical pancreatitis in a 23-year-old man of southern Indian descent who presented with recurrent attacks of pancreatitis with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a markedly dilated and tortuous MPD (arrow) with large intraductal stones (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple large areas of calcification and intraductal “stones” in the pancreatic head (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Coronal non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1000/77, 3-mm section thickness) shows a markedly dilated MPD <i>(D)</i>, with intraductal stones appearing as hypointense filling defects (arrowheads). Note the significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(d, e)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) <b>(d)</b> and ERCP images obtained after the injection of contrast material into the CBD (left) and MPD (right) <b>(e)</b> show gross pancreatic ductal dilatation with intraductal calculi (arrows). No pancreatic masses or ductal anomalies were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F4D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g04e.jpeg" height="1003" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4e.</b>  Tropical pancreatitis in a 23-year-old man of southern Indian descent who presented with recurrent attacks of pancreatitis with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a markedly dilated and tortuous MPD (arrow) with large intraductal stones (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple large areas of calcification and intraductal “stones” in the pancreatic head (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> Coronal non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1000/77, 3-mm section thickness) shows a markedly dilated MPD <i>(D)</i>, with intraductal stones appearing as hypointense filling defects (arrowheads). Note the significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(d, e)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) <b>(d)</b> and ERCP images obtained after the injection of contrast material into the CBD (left) and MPD (right) <b>(e)</b> show gross pancreatic ductal dilatation with intraductal calculi (arrows). No pancreatic masses or ductal anomalies were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F4E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g05a.jpeg" height="1221" width="1674" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Hereditary pancreatitis in an 18-year-old man with recurrent episodes of idiopathic acute pancreatitis. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT scans reveal multiple focal areas of punctate calcifications throughout the pancreatic parenchyma (arrows in <b>a</b>, arrowheads in <b>b</b>), findings that are nonspecific and suggest chronic calcific pancreatitis. However, the young age of the patient, the absence of any known predisposing factors, and the family history of pancreatitis favor a diagnosis of hereditary pancreatitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g05b.jpeg" height="1189" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Hereditary pancreatitis in an 18-year-old man with recurrent episodes of idiopathic acute pancreatitis. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> unenhanced CT scans reveal multiple focal areas of punctate calcifications throughout the pancreatic parenchyma (arrows in <b>a</b>, arrowheads in <b>b</b>), findings that are nonspecific and suggest chronic calcific pancreatitis. However, the young age of the patient, the absence of any known predisposing factors, and the family history of pancreatitis favor a diagnosis of hereditary pancreatitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g06a.jpeg" height="869" width="1224" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Acute pancreatitis in a 50-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase CT scan obtained before the patient had pancreatitis shows heterotopic pancreatic tissue anterior to the pancreas and arising exophytically from the prepyloric region of the gastric wall (arrow). The heterotopic tissue shows enhancement similar to that of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Venous phase CT scan obtained 3 months later also shows the heterotopic pancreatic tissue (arrow). Inflammatory changes with fluid (arrowheads) are seen surrounding the tissue, a finding that is suggestive of pancreatitis. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained at a lower level shows the fluid tracking around the duodenum and in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrows). Surgical resection of the lesion was performed. Results of histopathologic analysis confirmed heterotopic pancreatic tissue arising exophytically from the prepyloric region of the stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g06b.jpeg" height="1335" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Acute pancreatitis in a 50-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase CT scan obtained before the patient had pancreatitis shows heterotopic pancreatic tissue anterior to the pancreas and arising exophytically from the prepyloric region of the gastric wall (arrow). The heterotopic tissue shows enhancement similar to that of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Venous phase CT scan obtained 3 months later also shows the heterotopic pancreatic tissue (arrow). Inflammatory changes with fluid (arrowheads) are seen surrounding the tissue, a finding that is suggestive of pancreatitis. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained at a lower level shows the fluid tracking around the duodenum and in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrows). Surgical resection of the lesion was performed. Results of histopathologic analysis confirmed heterotopic pancreatic tissue arising exophytically from the prepyloric region of the stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g06c.jpeg" height="1347" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Acute pancreatitis in a 50-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Arterial phase CT scan obtained before the patient had pancreatitis shows heterotopic pancreatic tissue anterior to the pancreas and arising exophytically from the prepyloric region of the gastric wall (arrow). The heterotopic tissue shows enhancement similar to that of the pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Venous phase CT scan obtained 3 months later also shows the heterotopic pancreatic tissue (arrow). Inflammatory changes with fluid (arrowheads) are seen surrounding the tissue, a finding that is suggestive of pancreatitis. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained at a lower level shows the fluid tracking around the duodenum and in the pancreaticoduodenal groove (arrows). Surgical resection of the lesion was performed. Results of histopathologic analysis confirmed heterotopic pancreatic tissue arising exophytically from the prepyloric region of the stomach.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g07a.jpeg" height="1609" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  <i>Ascaris</i>-induced pancreatitis in a 45-year-old woman who presented with severe epigastric pain and a moderately elevated serum amylase level. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatograms (4500/985) (<b>b</b> obtained in a slightly more oblique plane than <b>a</b>) show a linear hypointense filling defect (arrow) within the distal CBD, a finding that is suggestive of <i>A lumbricoides</i> impacted within the duct. <b>(c)</b> Axial non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) shows peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow) with minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis secondary to biliary ascariasis. The worm was successfully removed with endoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g07b.jpeg" height="1596" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  <i>Ascaris</i>-induced pancreatitis in a 45-year-old woman who presented with severe epigastric pain and a moderately elevated serum amylase level. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatograms (4500/985) (<b>b</b> obtained in a slightly more oblique plane than <b>a</b>) show a linear hypointense filling defect (arrow) within the distal CBD, a finding that is suggestive of <i>A lumbricoides</i> impacted within the duct. <b>(c)</b> Axial non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) shows peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow) with minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis secondary to biliary ascariasis. The worm was successfully removed with endoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g07c.jpeg" height="1448" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  <i>Ascaris</i>-induced pancreatitis in a 45-year-old woman who presented with severe epigastric pain and a moderately elevated serum amylase level. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatograms (4500/985) (<b>b</b> obtained in a slightly more oblique plane than <b>a</b>) show a linear hypointense filling defect (arrow) within the distal CBD, a finding that is suggestive of <i>A lumbricoides</i> impacted within the duct. <b>(c)</b> Axial non-fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) shows peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow) with minimal pancreatic ductal dilatation (arrowhead), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis secondary to biliary ascariasis. The worm was successfully removed with endoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g08a.jpeg" height="1202" width="1620" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Acute pancreatitis in a 20-year-old man with cystic fibrosis who presented with severe abdominal pain and borderline elevated serum amylase level. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans show fatty replacement of the pancreas with minimal residual normal parenchyma in the tail region anteriorly (arrowhead in <b>a</b>). Arrow indicates peripancreatic inflammatory changes and fluid, findings that are consistent with a diagnosis of acute pancreatitis. Note also the foci of calcification within the pancreatic head (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans obtained after resolution of the acute pancreatitis (<b>d</b> obtained at the level of the pancreatic head) reveal changes of fatty replacement and calcification in the pancreatic head (arrow), findings that are characteristic of cystic fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g08b.jpeg" height="1253" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Acute pancreatitis in a 20-year-old man with cystic fibrosis who presented with severe abdominal pain and borderline elevated serum amylase level. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans show fatty replacement of the pancreas with minimal residual normal parenchyma in the tail region anteriorly (arrowhead in <b>a</b>). Arrow indicates peripancreatic inflammatory changes and fluid, findings that are consistent with a diagnosis of acute pancreatitis. Note also the foci of calcification within the pancreatic head (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans obtained after resolution of the acute pancreatitis (<b>d</b> obtained at the level of the pancreatic head) reveal changes of fatty replacement and calcification in the pancreatic head (arrow), findings that are characteristic of cystic fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g08c.jpeg" height="1321" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8c.</b>  Acute pancreatitis in a 20-year-old man with cystic fibrosis who presented with severe abdominal pain and borderline elevated serum amylase level. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans show fatty replacement of the pancreas with minimal residual normal parenchyma in the tail region anteriorly (arrowhead in <b>a</b>). Arrow indicates peripancreatic inflammatory changes and fluid, findings that are consistent with a diagnosis of acute pancreatitis. Note also the foci of calcification within the pancreatic head (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans obtained after resolution of the acute pancreatitis (<b>d</b> obtained at the level of the pancreatic head) reveal changes of fatty replacement and calcification in the pancreatic head (arrow), findings that are characteristic of cystic fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F8C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g08d.jpeg" height="1328" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8d.</b>  Acute pancreatitis in a 20-year-old man with cystic fibrosis who presented with severe abdominal pain and borderline elevated serum amylase level. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans show fatty replacement of the pancreas with minimal residual normal parenchyma in the tail region anteriorly (arrowhead in <b>a</b>). Arrow indicates peripancreatic inflammatory changes and fluid, findings that are consistent with a diagnosis of acute pancreatitis. Note also the foci of calcification within the pancreatic head (arrowhead in <b>b</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Contrast-enhanced venous phase CT scans obtained after resolution of the acute pancreatitis (<b>d</b> obtained at the level of the pancreatic head) reveal changes of fatty replacement and calcification in the pancreatic head (arrow), findings that are characteristic of cystic fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F8D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13c09a.jpeg" height="1044" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Pancreas divisum. <b>(a)</b> Drawing illustrates complete pancreas divisum, with the dorsal duct (arrowhead) draining the majority of the gland into the minor papilla. The smaller ventral duct (arrow) drains the head and uncinate process of the pancreas into the major papilla; the CBD also drains into the major papilla. <i>D</i> = duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Drawing illustrates incomplete pancreas divisum, which is considered to be a normal variant. A short communication exists between the dorsal duct (arrowhead), which drains the majority of the gland into the minor papilla, and the smaller ventral duct (arrow), which drains into the major papilla along with the CBD. <i>D</i> = duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13c09b.jpeg" height="1060" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Pancreas divisum. <b>(a)</b> Drawing illustrates complete pancreas divisum, with the dorsal duct (arrowhead) draining the majority of the gland into the minor papilla. The smaller ventral duct (arrow) drains the head and uncinate process of the pancreas into the major papilla; the CBD also drains into the major papilla. <i>D</i> = duodenum. <b>(b)</b> Drawing illustrates incomplete pancreas divisum, which is considered to be a normal variant. A short communication exists between the dorsal duct (arrowhead), which drains the majority of the gland into the minor papilla, and the smaller ventral duct (arrow), which drains into the major papilla along with the CBD. <i>D</i> = duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g10a.jpeg" height="1374" width="1656" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Acute pancreatitis secondary to pancreas divisum in a 25-year-old woman. The patient had suffered recurrent episodes of pancreatitis (three attacks in 1 year) with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a diffusely enlarged pancreas with peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal single-shot heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) shows the ventral pancreatic duct (arrowhead) draining into the major papilla along with the CBD. <b>(c)</b> Coronal single-shot heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) shows the dorsal pancreatic duct (arrowhead) draining the majority of the gland into the minor papilla with no demonstrable connection with the ventral duct.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g10b.jpeg" height="1317" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Acute pancreatitis secondary to pancreas divisum in a 25-year-old woman. The patient had suffered recurrent episodes of pancreatitis (three attacks in 1 year) with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a diffusely enlarged pancreas with peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal single-shot heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) shows the ventral pancreatic duct (arrowhead) draining into the major papilla along with the CBD. <b>(c)</b> Coronal single-shot heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) shows the dorsal pancreatic duct (arrowhead) draining the majority of the gland into the minor papilla with no demonstrable connection with the ventral duct.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g10c.jpeg" height="1328" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Acute pancreatitis secondary to pancreas divisum in a 25-year-old woman. The patient had suffered recurrent episodes of pancreatitis (three attacks in 1 year) with no known underlying predisposing factor. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a diffusely enlarged pancreas with peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal single-shot heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) shows the ventral pancreatic duct (arrowhead) draining into the major papilla along with the CBD. <b>(c)</b> Coronal single-shot heavily T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatogram (4500/985) shows the dorsal pancreatic duct (arrowhead) draining the majority of the gland into the minor papilla with no demonstrable connection with the ventral duct.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g11a.jpeg" height="1419" width="1692" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Chronic pancreatitis secondary to pancreas divisum in a 70-year-old woman. The patient had previously suffered multiple episodes of acute pancreatitis that were presumed to be idiopathic. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a diffusely dilated and tortuous pancreatic duct (arrows) with significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4600/990) <b>(b)</b> and axial T2-weighted MR image (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(c)</b> show the grossly dilated dorsal pancreatic duct <i>(P)</i> crossing anterior to the CBD (arrowhead) and draining into the minor papilla (arrow). The ventral duct was markedly atrophic and was not well visualized at MR imaging. A diagnosis of pancreas divisum was made, and subsequent ERCP revealed a small ventral duct opening into the major papilla. The minor papilla was stenotic and could not be cannulated with ERCP.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g11b.jpeg" height="1359" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Chronic pancreatitis secondary to pancreas divisum in a 70-year-old woman. The patient had previously suffered multiple episodes of acute pancreatitis that were presumed to be idiopathic. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a diffusely dilated and tortuous pancreatic duct (arrows) with significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4600/990) <b>(b)</b> and axial T2-weighted MR image (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(c)</b> show the grossly dilated dorsal pancreatic duct <i>(P)</i> crossing anterior to the CBD (arrowhead) and draining into the minor papilla (arrow). The ventral duct was markedly atrophic and was not well visualized at MR imaging. A diagnosis of pancreas divisum was made, and subsequent ERCP revealed a small ventral duct opening into the major papilla. The minor papilla was stenotic and could not be cannulated with ERCP.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g11c.jpeg" height="1406" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Chronic pancreatitis secondary to pancreas divisum in a 70-year-old woman. The patient had previously suffered multiple episodes of acute pancreatitis that were presumed to be idiopathic. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a diffusely dilated and tortuous pancreatic duct (arrows) with significant atrophy of the pancreatic parenchyma. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal MR cholangiopancreatogram (4600/990) <b>(b)</b> and axial T2-weighted MR image (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(c)</b> show the grossly dilated dorsal pancreatic duct <i>(P)</i> crossing anterior to the CBD (arrowhead) and draining into the minor papilla (arrow). The ventral duct was markedly atrophic and was not well visualized at MR imaging. A diagnosis of pancreas divisum was made, and subsequent ERCP revealed a small ventral duct opening into the major papilla. The minor papilla was stenotic and could not be cannulated with ERCP.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g12a.jpeg" height="1221" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma in a 44-year-old man who presented with acute left flank pain and laboratory evidence of pancreatitis. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced CT scans obtained at initial presentation as part of a low-dose CT study show peripancreatic inflammation localized around the pancreatic tail with thickened anterior pararenal fascia (arrow in <b>b</b>), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. The body and proximal tail of the pancreas are bulkier than the rest of the tail (arrowhead in <b>a</b>), a finding that should have raised suspicion for an underlying mass. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows residual inflammation around the pancreatic tail. A focal ill-defined hypoattenuating area is seen in the tail (arrow) with a mildly dilated MPD distal to it, findings that are suggestive of an underlying neoplasm. Extensive laboratory work-up did not reveal an underlying cause for acute pancreatitis. MR imaging was performed to address the suspicion raised at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial unenhanced (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a vague, heterogeneously hyperintense lesion at the junction of the body and tail of the pancreas (arrow) that remains unenhanced on the postcontrast image. Disproportionate dilatation of the MPD in the pancreatic tail with atrophy of the tail is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g12b.jpeg" height="1282" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma in a 44-year-old man who presented with acute left flank pain and laboratory evidence of pancreatitis. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced CT scans obtained at initial presentation as part of a low-dose CT study show peripancreatic inflammation localized around the pancreatic tail with thickened anterior pararenal fascia (arrow in <b>b</b>), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. The body and proximal tail of the pancreas are bulkier than the rest of the tail (arrowhead in <b>a</b>), a finding that should have raised suspicion for an underlying mass. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows residual inflammation around the pancreatic tail. A focal ill-defined hypoattenuating area is seen in the tail (arrow) with a mildly dilated MPD distal to it, findings that are suggestive of an underlying neoplasm. Extensive laboratory work-up did not reveal an underlying cause for acute pancreatitis. MR imaging was performed to address the suspicion raised at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial unenhanced (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a vague, heterogeneously hyperintense lesion at the junction of the body and tail of the pancreas (arrow) that remains unenhanced on the postcontrast image. Disproportionate dilatation of the MPD in the pancreatic tail with atrophy of the tail is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g12c.jpeg" height="1279" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12c.</b>  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma in a 44-year-old man who presented with acute left flank pain and laboratory evidence of pancreatitis. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced CT scans obtained at initial presentation as part of a low-dose CT study show peripancreatic inflammation localized around the pancreatic tail with thickened anterior pararenal fascia (arrow in <b>b</b>), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. The body and proximal tail of the pancreas are bulkier than the rest of the tail (arrowhead in <b>a</b>), a finding that should have raised suspicion for an underlying mass. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows residual inflammation around the pancreatic tail. A focal ill-defined hypoattenuating area is seen in the tail (arrow) with a mildly dilated MPD distal to it, findings that are suggestive of an underlying neoplasm. Extensive laboratory work-up did not reveal an underlying cause for acute pancreatitis. MR imaging was performed to address the suspicion raised at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial unenhanced (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a vague, heterogeneously hyperintense lesion at the junction of the body and tail of the pancreas (arrow) that remains unenhanced on the postcontrast image. Disproportionate dilatation of the MPD in the pancreatic tail with atrophy of the tail is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F12C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g12d.jpeg" height="1264" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12d.</b>  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma in a 44-year-old man who presented with acute left flank pain and laboratory evidence of pancreatitis. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced CT scans obtained at initial presentation as part of a low-dose CT study show peripancreatic inflammation localized around the pancreatic tail with thickened anterior pararenal fascia (arrow in <b>b</b>), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. The body and proximal tail of the pancreas are bulkier than the rest of the tail (arrowhead in <b>a</b>), a finding that should have raised suspicion for an underlying mass. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows residual inflammation around the pancreatic tail. A focal ill-defined hypoattenuating area is seen in the tail (arrow) with a mildly dilated MPD distal to it, findings that are suggestive of an underlying neoplasm. Extensive laboratory work-up did not reveal an underlying cause for acute pancreatitis. MR imaging was performed to address the suspicion raised at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial unenhanced (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a vague, heterogeneously hyperintense lesion at the junction of the body and tail of the pancreas (arrow) that remains unenhanced on the postcontrast image. Disproportionate dilatation of the MPD in the pancreatic tail with atrophy of the tail is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F12D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g12e.jpeg" height="1305" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12e.</b>  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma in a 44-year-old man who presented with acute left flank pain and laboratory evidence of pancreatitis. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced CT scans obtained at initial presentation as part of a low-dose CT study show peripancreatic inflammation localized around the pancreatic tail with thickened anterior pararenal fascia (arrow in <b>b</b>), findings that are consistent with acute pancreatitis. The body and proximal tail of the pancreas are bulkier than the rest of the tail (arrowhead in <b>a</b>), a finding that should have raised suspicion for an underlying mass. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows residual inflammation around the pancreatic tail. A focal ill-defined hypoattenuating area is seen in the tail (arrow) with a mildly dilated MPD distal to it, findings that are suggestive of an underlying neoplasm. Extensive laboratory work-up did not reveal an underlying cause for acute pancreatitis. MR imaging was performed to address the suspicion raised at contrast-enhanced CT. <b>(d, e)</b> Axial unenhanced (1030/80, 5-mm section thickness) <b>(d)</b> and contrast-enhanced (3.35/1.5, 3-mm section thickness) <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted MR images show a vague, heterogeneously hyperintense lesion at the junction of the body and tail of the pancreas (arrow) that remains unenhanced on the postcontrast image. Disproportionate dilatation of the MPD in the pancreatic tail with atrophy of the tail is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F12E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g13a.jpeg" height="1466" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Duodenal villous adenoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with acute abdominal pain. Clinical findings and laboratory test results were consistent with acute pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Conventional radiograph shows a subtle filling defect (arrowheads) projecting along the medial wall of the duodenum. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scans show a polypoidal mass (arrowheads) along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum obstructing the ampulla of Vater, with resultant acute pancreatitis and peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Virtual endoscopic image of the duodenum shows the mass with nodular projections along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum. Surgery was performed, and the results of histopathologic analysis confirmed duodenal villous adenoma with no foci of malignant change.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g13b.jpeg" height="1425" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Duodenal villous adenoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with acute abdominal pain. Clinical findings and laboratory test results were consistent with acute pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Conventional radiograph shows a subtle filling defect (arrowheads) projecting along the medial wall of the duodenum. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scans show a polypoidal mass (arrowheads) along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum obstructing the ampulla of Vater, with resultant acute pancreatitis and peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Virtual endoscopic image of the duodenum shows the mass with nodular projections along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum. Surgery was performed, and the results of histopathologic analysis confirmed duodenal villous adenoma with no foci of malignant change.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g13c.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13c.</b>  Duodenal villous adenoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with acute abdominal pain. Clinical findings and laboratory test results were consistent with acute pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Conventional radiograph shows a subtle filling defect (arrowheads) projecting along the medial wall of the duodenum. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scans show a polypoidal mass (arrowheads) along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum obstructing the ampulla of Vater, with resultant acute pancreatitis and peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Virtual endoscopic image of the duodenum shows the mass with nodular projections along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum. Surgery was performed, and the results of histopathologic analysis confirmed duodenal villous adenoma with no foci of malignant change.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F13C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.294085748/asset/images/g09jl13g13d.jpeg" height="1797" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13d.</b>  Duodenal villous adenoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with acute abdominal pain. Clinical findings and laboratory test results were consistent with acute pancreatitis. <b>(a)</b> Conventional radiograph shows a subtle filling defect (arrowheads) projecting along the medial wall of the duodenum. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scans show a polypoidal mass (arrowheads) along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum obstructing the ampulla of Vater, with resultant acute pancreatitis and peripancreatic inflammatory changes (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> Virtual endoscopic image of the duodenum shows the mass with nodular projections along the medial wall of the second part of the duodenum. Surgery was performed, and the results of histopathologic analysis confirmed duodenal villous adenoma with no foci of malignant change.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.294085748&amp;id=F13D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="name